\description{
Assess in- and out-of-sample predictive performance of generalized linear and generalized additive models with binary response variables and with or without random effects, using either repeated random holdout (Monte Carlo cross-validation) or bootstrap resampling with out-of-bag evaluation. Three performance statistics are reported: Brier scores (see the \code{rms} package documentation for details), which range from 0 to 1 with values closer to 0 indicating a better-predicting model and where sqrt(Brier score) is the average difference between the predicted probability and the observed value (0 or 1); AUC, an aggregated metric that evaluates how well a model classifies positive and negative outcomes at all possible probability cutoffs, ranging from 0 to 1 with values closer to 1 indicating a better classifier and where an AUC of 0.5 suggests performance no better than random guessing; and log loss (cross-entropy), which penalizes confident wrong predictions logarithmically and is particularly sensitive to miscalibration at the extremes of the predicted probability distribution, with lower values indicating better performance and no upper bound. Note that all performance measures are based on population-level predictions (i.e., random effects are ignored when present).

The three binary metrics each capture a different aspect of predictive performance and are most informative when interpreted together.

\verb{AUC (Area Under the ROC Curve)}: The probability that a randomly chosen positive case receives a higher predicted probability than a randomly chosen negative case, ranging from 0 (no discrimination) to 1 (perfect discrimination), and where an AUC of 0.5 indicates that a model predicts no better than random chance (and AUC <0.5 is worse than random). AUC is purely a measure of discrimination (the model's ability to rank cases by their probability of the outcome) and is insensitive to how well the predicted probabilities are calibrated in absolute terms.

\verb{Brier Score}: The mean squared difference between predicted probabilities and observed binary outcomes (0/1), ranging from 0 (perfect) to 1 (worst). The Brier score jointly rewards good discrimination and good calibration, penalizing confident but wrong predictions more heavily than uncertain ones. A model can have high AUC but a poor Brier score if its predicted probabilities are systematically too high or too low even while correctly ordering cases.

\verb{Log Loss (Binary Cross-Entropy)}: The negative mean log-likelihood of the observed outcomes under the predicted probabilities, where lower values indicate better performance. Like the Brier score, log loss rewards calibration, but its logarithmic scale means it penalizes extreme, confident mispredictions far more aggressively. Log loss is therefore the most sensitive of the three to cases where the model assigns near-zero probability to an outcome that actually occurs.

Reporting all three together is recommended: AUC reflects whether the model correctly separates cases from non-cases; Brier score provides an overall summary of probability accuracy on a squared-error scale; and log loss highlights whether the model is making any dangerously overconfident errors that the Brier score might underweight.
}
\note{
This function only supports binary 0/1 responses and does not currently support binomial models with cbind() or proportion responses. This function also supports models with spatial random effects (e.g, in glmmTMB), but it is much slower than for more conventional GLM(M)s and GAM(M)s.

\strong{Random effects and Jensen's inequality:} All predictions are population-level (i.e., random effects are set to zero via \code{re.form = ~0}). For models with random effects and a nonlinear link function such as the logit, backtransforming the linear predictor to the probability scale introduces a systematic bias in the predicted mean probability. This occurs because Jensen's inequality implies that \code{E[plogis(eta)] != plogis(E[eta])} for any random variable \code{eta}. The direction and magnitude of this bias depend on the curvature of the inverse-logit function at the linear predictor value, and grow with random effect variance. Consistent negative patterns in Brier score or log loss relative to the null model baseline may partly reflect this structural property of the GLMM. To obtain bias-corrected marginal predictions for \code{glmmTMB} models, set \code{bias_adjust = "tmb"}, which applies the generic bias correction of Thorson & Kristensen (2016) via TMB's automatic differentiation. Note that \code{bias_adjust = "manual"} is not supported for binomial models as the analytical lognormal correction is not valid for logit-link models. Bias correction is not available for \code{lme4} or \code{mgcv} models; users requiring bias correction for these model types are encouraged to refit in \code{glmmTMB}.

\strong{Random slopes:} For models with random slopes, \code{bias_adjust = "tmb"} is the only appropriate correction option, as TMB's automatic differentiation correctly integrates over the full random effect covariance structure including slope variance. The Jensen bias varies by observation in random slopes models as a function of the covariate associated with the slope, making a scalar correction inappropriate.

\strong{Correction factor and out-of-sample leakage:} For \code{bias_adjust = "tmb"}, predictions are conditioned on the full RE structure (\code{re.form = NULL}) using BLUPs estimated from each refitted training model. This means the correction implicitly incorporates information about the RE variance structure from the training data, which introduces a minor form of information leakage into out-of-sample performance metrics. As with \code{bias_adjust = "manual"} in \code{bias_precision()}, this is considered an acceptable tradeoff: the primary purpose of bias correction in this context is diagnostic confirmation that Jensen's inequality is the source of observed metric patterns, and stable corrected metrics are more informative than strictly pure but potentially unstable out-of-sample estimates.

\strong{Conditional predictions:} By default, both in-sample and out-of-sample predictions are made marginally (\code{re.form = ~0}) to assess population-level generalization. Setting \code{conditional_predictions = TRUE} switches both to conditional predictions (\code{re.form = NULL}, \code{allow.new.levels = TRUE}), using the random effect estimates from the refitted training model for all predictions. Since GLAMMGoF's holdout CV splits rows within groups, the training model has RE estimates for all groups in the test set. The gap between in-sample and out-of-sample metrics reflects genuine row-level overfitting rather than any marginal vs conditional distinction.

\strong{Recommended workflow:} The following stepwise workflow is recommended for assessing predictive performance of a glmmTMB binomial GLMM. See the package vignette for a fully worked example.

Step 1 -- Run with defaults (\code{bias_adjust = "none"}, \code{conditional_predictions = FALSE}): assess population-level predictive generalization using Brier score, AUC, and log loss relative to null model baselines.

Step 2 (optional) -- Re-run with \code{bias_adjust = "tmb"} to apply TMB's automatic differentiation bias correction for Jensen's inequality on the logit scale. Note: this is considerably slower than the default and is most relevant when random effect variance is large. Note that \code{bias_adjust = "manual"} is not available for binomial models.

Step 3 (optional) -- Re-run with \code{conditional_predictions = TRUE} to assess within-group classification accuracy using estimated random effects. This measures how well the model interpolates within observed groups rather than generalizing to new ones.
}
\references{
Thorson, J.T. and Kristensen, K. (2016) Implementing a generic method for bias correction in statistical models using random effects, with spatial and population dynamics examples. \emph{Fisheries Research}, 175, 66--74.
